					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/khym-chanur" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(163438); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=163438&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226246" alt="Khym Chanur" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=163438)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/khym-chanur" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(163438); return false;" >Khym Chanur</a></span> <span class="odate time_1340332607 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">22 Jun 2012 02:36</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1486712">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Hostile Extraterrestrials (HEs) will possess no technology forbidden by the laws of physics.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Since both Dr Wondertainment and The Factory can mass-produce anomalies, I don't think this would be a reasonable assumption. I think better rationals for this point would be: 1) you can't do any planning if you throw into the scenario &quot;the HEs might have lots and lots of unknown anomalies, which being unknown could be capable of anything&quot;, and 2) if the HEs have mass-produced anomalous technology and weapons then Earth/humanity is unavoidably screwed, so we should focus our planning on scenarios where there's actually a chance of avoiding becoming screwed.</p>

							</div>

								
					
